metadata.name: stacks #99
metadata.description:
An exploration of vernacular architectural forms and combinatorial logics. If the roof form is typically what gives a building its character (i.e., its primary reading in a public-facing elevation), we can play with those proportions to achieve a particular reading. Square proportions become domestic, while shallower gables suggest more industrial typologies, narrower ones may even feel religious. Mixing a variety of proportions together allow for a proto-urban cacophony of elevational readings. These generative compositions play with both existing perceptions of the built environment as well as imaginary potentials of future architectures to come.

As impossible as these compositions may seem, they are fully realized as 3D forms, extruded at various lengths, all connected to a fictional ‚Äúground‚Äù. They are rendered using an elevation oblique projection, a form of parallel projection that visually distorts the geometry to show accurate depth and a true frontal elevation.

Press 's' in live mode to save a PNG.

metadata.name: Inner Perception #110
metadata.description:
Each generated artwork of this collection showcases a different perspective on a single scene. The collection highlights the diversity and subjectivity of human perception, revealing how our individual experiences, perspectives, and interpretations shape the way we see the world. "Inner Perception" invites viewers to reflect on their own perspectives and promotes a deeper understanding of the impact that personal interpretation has on shaping our perceptions of reality.

Use buttons ("2" - 4000px, "3" - 8000px, "4" - 12000px, "5" - 16000px) to change canvas size and "s" to download image as PNG

Created with p5.js

metadata.name: fields, sketches #93
metadata.description:
The third and final part of our generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022

metadata.name: FairyCells II #233
metadata.description:
FairyCells II is intended as a logical continuation of the first FairyCells series. By dropping the plotter drawing constraint, new perspectives for exploration appeared.
This is how these cells began to intertwine, live together, mutate and change color, like an evolving system.

What surprises me the most in this new series, is the stories appearing behind each new composition. See how these abstracts shapes can come to life and narrate us things through our imagination.

Each color palette takes us into a different world, drawing a very specific atmosphere.

As me, let yourself be carried away by these stories üí´ !

Artwork by Julien_Espagnon, 2022.

Control : Press ¬´ S ¬ª to save the image as a PNG.

Head to chaos

This FairyCells project comes to end this story with this last chapter.

metadata.name: Anima #5
metadata.description:
A dream to behold
of math and light,

a story to be told
of infinite and the might,

an ode to the unknown
and the mysteries it has shown.

Longing for the embrace
of heaven and its starry wonder,

in this outer space
feeling no more torn asunder.

- To our adored ones.

‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê

"Anima" is the Italian/Latin word for "soul".

The core of this generative artwork consists solely of overlapping circles. 
Prime numbers are crucial to the formation of these almost infinite shapes.
Generation can take from a few seconds to a few minutes depending on your device.
The default resolution is 1024x1024 pixels.

‚Ä¢ In live mode, add &scale=[ùíè] to the url to scale the artwork [1,2,3,4,5] times
‚Ä¢ press 's' / double click / double tap to save the image

I invite the most adventurous to explore the finer details by rendering at max scale.
Glitches will likely be generated due to some out-of-range values; I did not to fix them in honor of the imperfect.

metadata.name: Conjunction Of The Spheres #132
metadata.description:
This project is my first one in a series of algorithmic studies. Inspired by the work of Casey Reas and his "Process Compendium", it starts with a very simple text description of an algorithmic process. In this case, I came up this description:

"Place N circles randomly on the canvas. Select a point on each of the circles, and rotate it around its circle. At each step, draw a random line that connects all the points"

Each step is drawn with very low opacity, and is repeated a large number of times (these pieces draw around 6 million lines). Eventually, complex structures, shapes and patterns appear, that were impossible to predict from the text description alone: this is an emergent system.

The text description voluntarily leaves things open to interpretation: how many points ? which colors to use ? which rules for the drawing opacity and line weight ? Do all points move at the same speed ? Can they accelerate ? Are the circles allowed to extend past the canvas boundaries ?

This makes the process capable of interesting variations, as well as reusable: another artist implementation of the same description would most likely give very different artworks.

Despite the apparent simplicity of the description, this collection ended up being a real challenge. Drawing millions of lines with low opacity turned out to be impossible without a GPU. WebGL is required.

This token uses the regl.js library. The outputs are rendered at 2400x2400 and should be viewed at that size. You can generate high resolution outputs, up to 8000px, by adding &size=XXXX to the URL.

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #25
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive ‚Äî Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees‚Äô Schotter (1968)‚Äî a classic piece of generative art history ‚Äî as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver‚Äôd on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there‚Äôs a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares ‚Äî since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‚Äòdithering‚Äô can be larger than a single ‚Äòpixel‚Äô size ‚Äî when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND
